<subSubSection pageId="279" pageNumber="884" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="279.[2054,2648,294,717]" box="[2054,2647,417,442]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884">This enigmatic genus, originally con-</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="279.[2054,2648,294,717]" box="[2055,2644,447,481]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884">
sidered as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1868" box="[2236,2409,447,481]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Chiropodomys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="279" pageNumber="884" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Chiropodomys</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName box="[2491,2640,447,481]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Vandeleuria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="279" pageNumber="884" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Vandeleuria</taxonomicName>
,
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="279.[2054,2648,294,717]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884">
is poorly known. X. Misonne in 1974 indicated that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Anthony" authorityYear="1941" box="[2245,2343,527,561]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Vernaya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="279" pageNumber="884" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Vernaya</taxonomicName>
was close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Peters" authorityYear="1868" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Chiropodomys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="279" pageNumber="884" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Chiropodomys</taxonomicName>
with regard to dental morphology. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="G. M. Allen" baseAuthorityYear="1927" box="[2059,2156,609,638]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Vernaya" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="279" pageNumber="884" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="fulva">V. fulva</taxonomicName>
is considered as incertae sedis and has never been investigated genetically. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="279" pageNumber="884" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="279.[1441,2646,728,1467]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6888659" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6888659" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6888659/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="279" pageNumber="884" startId="279.[1442,1614,728,757]" targetBox="[1439,2030,305,709]" targetPageId="279">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1442,1618,728,757]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884">Distribution.</emphasis>
C &amp; SC China (S Gansu, SW Shaanxi, Sichuan, and Yunnan) and NE Myanmar
</caption>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="279" pageNumber="884" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="279.[1441,2646,728,1467]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1442,1700,811,836]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head—body 58-80 mm, tail 100-140 mm, ear 17 mm, hindfoot 16-18 mm. No specific data are available for body weight. Vernay’s Climbing Mouse is small, rich brown orange dorsally, fulvous orange on sides, and gray or buffy white ventrally. Pelage is very soft and thick. Tail is very long, 170-200% of head-body length, dark, covered by brown hairs, and darker above than below. Thumb has flat nail. Skull has short muzzle and high and wide braincase. Females have eight pairs of mammae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[1442,2417,1082,1111]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="279.[1441,2646,728,1467]" box="[1442,2417,1082,1111]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1442,1553,1082,1111]" pageId="279" pageNumber="884">Habitat.</emphasis>
Mountain forests with low shrubs and thickets above 2100 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
